"{\"uid\": \"si.com-olympics-triathlon-seine-water-quality-paris-olympics\", \"text\": \"Good morning, I\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m Dan Gartland. I hope all the triathletes brought some Pepto Bismol with them to the Olympic Village.  In today\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s SI:AM:  \\u00f0\\u009f\\u00a5\\u0087Gold again for U.S. women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s gymnastics\\u00f0\\u009f\\u00a4\\u0094A \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cslow pool\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d in Paris?\\u00f0\\u009f\\u0094\\u0084MLB trade deadline wrap-up  One of the biggest questions entering these Olympic Games was whether organizers\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099 bold plan to hold the swimming portion of the triathlon in the Seine would backfire. On Wednesday, after months of doubts over the quality of the water in the river, both the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s and women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s races went off as planned. Mostly.  For background, the decision to use the Seine for the swimming leg of the triathlon\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094and the open-water marathon swim next week\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094was one of the most controversial aspects of these Games. If it worked out, it would lead to the spectacular sight of a pack of more than 50 athletes swimming right through the heart of Paris. But there was a big problem:the quality of the water.  The Seine has long been a highly polluted waterway, and getting it Olympics-ready was a difficult and very expensive undertaking. Paris spent $1.5 billion on a variety of projects designed to improve the water quality. That included upgrades to water treatment plants, renovating the city\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s 14th-century sewer system and building a catch basin designed to prevent untreated waste from entering the river.  And the project mostly worked. Water quality in the Seine did improve, but it was still highly variable. After heavy rains,the amount of E. coli and Enterococci bacteria in the waterwould increase. In the months before the Games, the bacteria levels in the river were still too high for safe swimming, but organizers hoped that drier, sunnier summer weather would work in their favor. It didn\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099t turn out that way.  The heavy rain that viewers saw during the opening ceremony on Friday continued into Saturday and caused bacteria levels to spike. The planned triathlon practice sessions scheduled for Sunday and Monday were canceled due to the water quality and the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s race, originally scheduled for Tuesday, had to be postponed.  That led to a triathlon doubleheader on Wednesday, with the women going off at 8 a.m. local time as planned and the men following at 10:45 a.m. local time. France\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Cassandre Beaugrand took gold in the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s race, followed by Switzerland\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Julie Derron in second and Great Britain\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Beth Potter in third. Great Britain\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Alex Yee won the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s race, with New Zealand\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Hayden Wilde and France\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s L\\u00c3\\u00a9o Bergere taking silver and bronze, respectively.  It was a relief for all the athletes, who had been upset about the possibility that the swimming portion of the race could be scrapped entirely and the event changed to a duathlon. But we\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll wait to see if organizers were right to hold the race as planned.  Paris 2024 and World Triathlon said in a joint statement before the first race that they had been given the go-ahead to proceed after receiving the results of a water quality test at 3:20 a.m. local time. But Paris organizing committee official Aur\\u00c3\\u00a9lie Merle revealed to reporters on Tuesday that the test samples used to determine the water quality are collected nearly 24 hours before the decision is made about whether it is safe to proceed with the swim. Thunderstorms rolled through Paris overnight Tuesday, after the water sample had been collected, so the water the athletes swam in Wednesday morning could have been more polluted than the most recent test results showed.  Beaugrand, the French winner of the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s race, dismissed concerns about the quality of the water.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI have no doubts about the quality of the Seine,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cWe\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve swum in worse water.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  But that attitude was not shared by all of her colleagues. American Taylor Spivey, who finished 10th in the women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s race,told NBC Newsthat she swallowed \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009ca ton of water.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ve taken a lot of probiotics over the past month,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d she added. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cSo we\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099ll see how it goes.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  South Africa\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Jamie Riddle, the 25th-place finisher in the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s race, left less to the imagination.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099m definitely going to be visiting the bathroom later,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d he told reporters,according to Reuters. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI swallowed gallons and gallons of water, so that\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s gonna be a fun post-race party.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u00a6 things I saw yesterday:  5.Muggsy Bogues\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s responseto the viral photo of 7'4\\\" Victor Wembanyama being guarded by 5'6\\\" Yuki Togashi.4.All 16 saves Minnesota United goalkeeper Dayne St. Clairmade in a shutout victory.3.Jazz Chisholm Jr.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s fourth home runin three games with the Yankees.2.The New Zealandwomen\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s rugby team\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s hakaafter winning the gold medal.1.Alex Sedrick\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s long runthat secured the bronze medal for the U.S. women\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s rugby team.  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Dan Gartland writes Sports Illustrated\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s flagship daily newsletter, SI:AM, and is the host of the \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cStadium Wonders\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d video series. He joined the SI staff in 2014, having previously been published on Deadspin and Slate. Gartland, a graduate of Fordham University, is a former Sports Jeopardy! champion (Season 1, Episode 5).  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"